00:24:50,296 --> 00:24:55,726
down this symbolism of words
and putting the concreteness


491
00:24:55,726 --> 00:24:56,836
of pictures into that.


492
00:24:57,646 --> 00:25:00,586
But this is actually a different
level of symbolism at play here.


493
00:25:00,586 --> 00:25:02,336
This is a symbolism of grammar.


494
00:25:03,146 --> 00:25:06,616
And grammar is something
that's so abstract,


495
00:25:06,616 --> 00:25:07,856
and there are the
rules of grammar.


496
00:25:07,906 --> 00:25:09,876
And those rules of
grammar are so abstract


497
00:25:09,876 --> 00:25:13,296
that they're even very hard
for us as native speakers


498
00:25:13,296 --> 00:25:14,976
to explain and to understand.


499
00:25:15,886 --> 00:25:18,026
You know? For example, if
you take this sentence,


500
00:25:18,026 --> 00:25:20,996
"I want to eat,"
what's the meaning


501
00:25:20,996 --> 00:25:22,816
of the word "to"
in the sentence?


502
00:25:22,906 --> 00:25:25,686
You know, if you asked me,
I wouldn't have an idea.


503
00:25:25,726 --> 00:25:27,386
It's just a word that's there


504
00:25:27,386 --> 00:25:30,496
because it's ungrammatical
if it wasn't there.


505
00:25:31,516 --> 00:25:33,726
[ Laughter ]


506
00:25:34,226 --> 00:25:37,126
If you take these sentences,
"The window broke," and,


507
00:25:37,126 --> 00:25:39,396
"He broke the window,"
it's interesting, you know,


508
00:25:39,396 --> 00:25:41,396
these two sentences are
both grammatically correct.


509
00:25:41,636 --> 00:25:43,926
But the object that's
breaking is actually the same.


510
00:25:43,926 --> 00:25:45,746
Right? The window is the
object that's breaking.


511
00:25:45,746 --> 00:25:49,466
Why is it that it appears on one
side of "broke" on one sentence


512
00:25:49,466 --> 00:25:51,356
and on the other side of
"broke" in the other sentence?


513
00:25:51,966 --> 00:25:56,146
Or if you take this sentence,
"I eat," the past tense


514
00:25:56,146 --> 00:25:59,026
of this is obviously, "I ate."


515
00:25:59,156 --> 00:26:01,706
But if you negate this sentence,
if you say, "I didn't eat,"


516
00:26:03,306 --> 00:26:05,796
why is it wrong to
say, "I didn't ate"?


517
00:26:06,826 --> 00:26:11,926
Right? So there are these
meta-rules at play here.


518
00:26:12,006 --> 00:26:15,586
There are these things
that go beyond the rules


519
00:26:15,586 --> 00:26:18,306
of which word presents
which meaning.


520
00:26:18,926 --> 00:26:20,466
There are these meta-rules
of grammar.


521
00:26:21,056 --> 00:26:23,116
And this was actually
very frustrating to us.


522
00:26:23,206 --> 00:26:28,026
We went out behind the
pursuit Avaz with the intention


523
00:26:28,026 --> 00:26:30,356
of giving communication,
full communication,


524
00:26:30,396 --> 00:26:32,396
equal communication to
kids with disabilities.


525
00:26:32,726 --> 00:26:36,056
And we knew that our mission
was actually being completely


526
00:26:36,056 --> 00:26:39,416
underfulfilled if we were
only giving them words


527
00:26:39,646 --> 00:26:42,946
without giving them the
ability to also create sentences


528
00:26:42,946 --> 00:26:44,046
and to put these words together.


529
00:26:44,046 --> 00:26:47,446
The problem was that,
unlike in the case of Avaz,


530
00:26:48,386 --> 00:26:50,166
there was actually
very little research,


531
00:26:50,466 --> 00:26:53,946
very little theory behind
how you can teach children


532
00:26:53,946 --> 00:26:55,636
with autism grammar,
how you can teach them


533
00:26:55,636 --> 00:26:56,486
to put words together.


534
00:26:57,076 --> 00:26:59,926
We trawled through all of
the scientific journals.


535
00:26:59,926 --> 00:27:01,506
We went to all of the
scientific conferences.


536
00:27:01,536 --> 00:27:03,416
But very little insights
that people had got.


537
00:27:05,556 --> 00:27:09,816
The insight that kind of
triggered a lot of ideas


538
00:27:09,816 --> 00:27:14,286
in our head quite consistently
came from the work of somebody


539
00:27:14,286 --> 00:27:17,336
who lived 2,500 years ago.


540
00:27:17,766 --> 00:27:19,756
He was an Indian philosopher.


541
00:27:21,156 --> 00:27:23,976
I don't know if he
exactly looks like this.


542
00:27:24,071 --> 00:27:26,071
[ Laughter ]


543
00:27:26,126 --> 00:27:28,846
The Indian government put out
a stamp about him in 2004.


544
00:27:29,026 --> 00:27:32,206
He has the unfortunate
distinction of sharing his name


545
00:27:32,206 --> 00:27:33,106
with a kind of sandwich.


546
00:27:33,106 --> 00:27:33,946
It's called Panini.


547
00:27:34,031 --> 00:27:36,031
[ Laughter ]


548
00:27:36,046 --> 00:27:41,906
But Panini lived in -- it didn't
mean "sandwich" back then.


549
00:27:42,031 --> 00:27:44,031
[ Laugther ]


550
00:27:44,046 --> 00:27:46,986
Panini lived around 500 BC.


551
00:27:47,216 --> 00:27:49,446
And Panini did something
which was phenomenal,


552
00:27:49,516 --> 00:27:51,886
which is unprecedented
even today.


553
00:27:52,416 --> 00:27:55,736
He took a language, the
language of Sanskrit,


554
00:27:57,206 --> 00:28:03,396
and he created a concise,
complete, consistent set


555
00:28:03,396 --> 00:28:08,756
of rules -- 4,000 rules -- that
described the entire language.


556
00:28:10,626 --> 00:28:14,736
OK, so he had this set of 4,000
rules, and those rules are


557
00:28:14,796 --> 00:28:16,286
of course still relevant today.


558
00:28:16,616 --> 00:28:20,586
But with these 4,000 rules, if
you apply these 4,000 rules,


559
00:28:21,006 --> 00:28:23,496
any sentence that you
created would be guaranteed


560
00:28:23,496 --> 00:28:25,066
to be grammatically-correct
Sanskrit.


561
00:28:26,346 --> 00:28:28,686
And conversely, any
grammatically-correct sentence


562
00:28:28,686 --> 00:28:32,326
in Sanskrit, any sentence, any
book, any verbal reference,


563
00:28:32,326 --> 00:28:36,396
any grammatically-correct
Sanskrit could be explained


564
00:28:36,766 --> 00:28:38,156
with these 4,000 rules.


565
00:28:38,646 --> 00:28:40,916
It was almost like he had
written a computer program


566
00:28:41,736 --> 00:28:42,986
to generate Sanskrit.


567
00:28:43,496 --> 00:28:48,626
So that codification of a
language and the way that he did


568
00:28:48,626 --> 00:28:50,156
that was absolutely beautiful.


569
00:28:50,156 --> 00:28:51,306
It was phenomenal.


570
00:28:51,566 --> 00:28:54,486
But that codification of
Sanskrit gave us the first clue


571
00:28:54,916 --> 00:28:56,566
that maybe this is an
approach that we can take.


572
00:28:56,566 --> 00:28:58,846
Maybe we can codify the
rules of grammar and put it


573
00:28:58,846 --> 00:29:01,306
into a computer in some
sense and see if we can use


574
00:29:01,306 --> 00:29:04,816
that to give kids with
autism an access to grammar.


575
00:29:05,886 --> 00:29:08,186
But even though we
had that insight,


576
00:29:09,136 --> 00:29:11,796
the other missing component
was really the user experience.


577
00:29:11,796 --> 00:29:14,016
How could we get kids to
interact with grammar?


578
00:29:14,836 --> 00:29:18,996
And the answer to that really
appropriately came when I was


579
00:29:19,066 --> 00:29:22,716
in a school for kids with autism
and I happened to interact


580
00:29:22,796 --> 00:29:26,376
with -- I happened to
be present, you know,


581
00:29:26,376 --> 00:29:29,136
where there was this little
girl, and there was her mother,


582
00:29:29,136 --> 00:29:30,236
and there were her teachers.


583
00:29:30,926 --> 00:29:33,066
And this girl, you
know, she had autism


584
00:29:33,066 --> 00:29:34,716
and she was almost
completely nonverbal.


585
00:29:34,716 --> 00:29:35,986
But once in a while,
she could speak.


586
00:29:36,556 --> 00:29:37,836
And that's what happened
that day.


587
00:29:37,836 --> 00:29:41,246
She jumped up and she
said the word "eat".


588
00:29:41,956 --> 00:29:43,426
And there was no
context to this.


589
00:29:43,806 --> 00:29:45,296
She just finished
eating her lunch,


590
00:29:45,426 --> 00:29:47,186
so her teacher thought
perhaps she wanted


591
00:29:47,186 --> 00:29:48,276
to talk about her lunch.


592
00:29:48,756 --> 00:29:51,296
So they tried to get
her to communicate


593
00:29:51,296 --> 00:29:52,996
about her lunch on Avaz.


594
00:29:52,996 --> 00:29:54,996
But it was very clear
that, you know,


595
00:29:54,996 --> 00:29:56,266
that was not what she
was trying to say.


596
00:29:57,206 --> 00:29:59,476
So we were all standing
there and trying to figure


597
00:29:59,476 --> 00:30:01,566
out what she meant
by the word "eat".


598
00:30:01,636 --> 00:30:05,006
And then her mother started
asking her questions.


599
00:30:06,396 --> 00:30:08,816
So her mother said,
"OK, eat what?


600
00:30:09,296 --> 00:30:09,956
Eat lunch?


601
00:30:10,006 --> 00:30:10,656
Eat breakfast?


602
00:30:10,746 --> 00:30:11,496
Eat snacks?"


603
00:30:12,126 --> 00:30:14,936
And then the girl took out her
iPad, and she took out Avaz


604
00:30:14,936 --> 00:30:16,416
and she pointed to
the word "ice cream".


605
00:30:17,646 --> 00:30:19,596
And then her mother
asked, "OK, who eats?


606
00:30:19,736 --> 00:30:21,576
You eat? Someone else eats?"


607
00:30:21,986 --> 00:30:24,506
You know? And then she
pointed to the word "I".


608
00:30:24,506 --> 00:30:27,356
And then her mother
was like, "Eat when?


609
00:30:27,356 --> 00:30:28,256
Eat now? Eat later?"


610
00:30:28,256 --> 00:30:31,106
And it turned out that
this particular girl wanted


611
00:30:31,136 --> 00:30:33,616
to eat ice cream on her
way back home from school.


612
00:30:34,636 --> 00:30:37,786
Now it's not often that
I can pinpoint the moment


613
00:30:37,786 --> 00:30:39,376
when the lightbulb
goes off in my head.


614
00:30:39,656 --> 00:30:42,836
But in this particular case,
I remember this episode almost


615
00:30:42,836 --> 00:30:43,756
like it happened yesterday.


616
00:30:44,706 --> 00:30:49,266
Because what struck me was
that feeling of realization --


617
00:30:49,266 --> 00:30:53,416
that realization that this
mother had gotten this girl


618
00:30:53,416 --> 00:30:56,966
to communicate what she
wanted without using grammar.


619
00:30:58,616 --> 00:31:02,026
I mean, this girl could not put
more than one word together.


620
00:31:02,026 --> 00:31:04,366
She could not put multiple words
together to create sentences.


621
00:31:04,436 --> 00:31:06,436
She could not select
different forms of words.


622
00:31:06,736 --> 00:31:08,386
She did not know what
the meaning of "to" was.


623
00:31:08,926 --> 00:31:12,846
She did not know the way in
which English grammar worked.


624
00:31:12,846 --> 00:31:16,426
It's almost as if her mother had
peered into her head and figured


625
00:31:16,426 --> 00:31:21,936
out what the meaning was
that she wanted to convey.


626
00:31:21,936 --> 00:31:24,776
So this was the other
part of the puzzle for me.


627
00:31:25,476 --> 00:31:27,386
You know, and I took this idea


628
00:31:27,386 --> 00:31:31,056
that we could really represent
meaning without grammar


629
00:31:31,516 --> 00:31:34,536
if we joined words together
using questions and answers.


630
00:31:34,736 --> 00:31:37,886
And I combined that with
the algorithms that came


631
00:31:37,886 --> 00:31:42,116
from my study of Panini and all
of the resource in linguistics


632
00:31:42,116 --> 00:31:43,946
and the resource in
neuroscience that had been


633
00:31:43,946 --> 00:31:44,936
over the last few years.


634
00:31:45,646 --> 00:31:48,786
And I put that together
to create an app.


635
00:31:48,786 --> 00:31:51,296
It took me three years to
actually create this app.


636
00:31:51,296 --> 00:31:52,646
I started in 2012.


637
00:31:52,646 --> 00:31:55,256
It was in 2015 that the
pieces finally came together.


638
00:31:55,356 --> 00:31:59,716
And in 2016, we put
this app out --


639
00:31:59,806 --> 00:32:01,166
this year, just a
few months ago.


640
00:32:02,086 --> 00:32:03,486
It's called FreeSpeech.


641
00:32:04,076 --> 00:32:07,136
And let me show you a quick
demo of FreeSpeech to explain


642
00:32:07,136 --> 00:32:08,866
to you how we solved
this problem.


643
00:32:20,206 --> 00:32:21,936
OK, so this is the
FreeSpeech App.


644
00:32:22,156 --> 00:32:25,146
And you can see that it
has pictures the same way


645
00:32:25,146 --> 00:32:26,346
that Avaz has pictures.


646
00:32:26,346 --> 00:32:29,146
In fact, if I tap on the
More Words button here


647
00:32:29,146 --> 00:32:32,956
on the bottom-left, it has all
of the pictures that Avaz has.


648
00:32:33,746 --> 00:32:36,406
But unlike Avaz, when
you construct a sentence


649
00:32:36,406 --> 00:32:39,066
in FreeSpeech, you
don't have to start


650
00:32:39,066 --> 00:32:40,456
at the beginning
of the sentence.


651
00:32:40,456 --> 00:32:42,356
In fact, you can start
anywhere in the sentence.


652
00:32:42,356 --> 00:32:45,586
So, for example, supposing
I pick the word "take"


653
00:32:46,746 --> 00:32:48,726
and I drop it here
on the screen.


654
00:32:49,176 --> 00:32:50,166
Here's the interesting part.


655
00:32:50,376 --> 00:32:50,886
>> Take


656
00:32:51,376 --> 00:32:55,626
>> The app actually gives you
this lattice this scaffold


657
00:32:56,106 --> 00:32:59,236
of questions around the word
that you've just dropped


658
00:33:00,086 --> 00:33:02,986
so that you can add more words
to create a sentence out of it.


659
00:33:02,986 --> 00:33:05,666
It's very similar to what
the girl's mother was doing.


660
00:33:05,666 --> 00:33:08,886
For example, if I drag
the word "teacher"


661
00:33:09,086 --> 00:33:11,706
and I put it into
the word "who".


662
00:33:12,186 --> 00:33:13,416
>> The teacher takes.


663
00:33:13,786 --> 00:33:15,856
>> It automatically
constructs a sentence


664
00:33:16,256 --> 00:33:17,706
with that specific meaning.


665
00:33:17,706 --> 00:33:18,806
It says, "The teacher takes."


666
00:33:19,306 --> 00:33:22,506
I can take the word "book", and
if I put it into the "what",


667
00:33:22,816 --> 00:33:25,496
it will say, "The
teacher takes the book."


668
00:33:25,696 --> 00:33:29,186
And if I take the word "school"
and if I drop it on the word


669
00:33:29,286 --> 00:33:34,506
"to", it will say, "The teacher
takes the book to the school."


670
00:33:35,286 --> 00:33:38,076
Let me show you a slightly
more complicated example.


671
00:33:38,326 --> 00:33:41,306
So, supposing we pick the
word "want", and let's put


672
00:33:41,306 --> 00:33:44,376
that in here, it pops up
all of these questions.


673
00:33:45,386 --> 00:33:49,026
And I can take the word "parent"
and I put it into the "who".


674
00:33:49,026 --> 00:33:50,636
If I put into "want",
for example,


675
00:33:50,636 --> 00:33:52,326
it will say, "Want the parent."


676
00:33:52,506 --> 00:33:55,896
But if I took that from that
location and if I put it


677
00:33:55,896 --> 00:33:58,526
into the "who", it will
say, "The parent wants."


678
00:33:58,526 --> 00:34:00,146
And you see that every
time you add a word,


679
00:34:00,236 --> 00:34:02,366
it actually gives you
even more questions.


680
00:34:02,366 --> 00:34:03,496
So more questions pop up.


681
00:34:03,496 --> 00:34:05,276
So you can see that
there's a "whose"


682
00:34:05,276 --> 00:34:07,346
which is next to "parent".


683
00:34:07,346 --> 00:34:09,766
So if I tap that, it will
ask you the question,


684
00:34:09,766 --> 00:34:10,666
"Whose parent wants?"


685
00:34:10,666 --> 00:34:13,116
And then I can drag the
word "she", for example,


686
00:34:13,116 --> 00:34:14,485
and drop that in here.


687
00:34:14,485 --> 00:34:16,386
It will say, "Her parent wants."


688
00:34:16,835 --> 00:34:20,036
If I tap this little button on
the top-left corner of "parent",


689
00:34:20,036 --> 00:34:21,755
I can convert that
into a plural.


690
00:34:21,755 --> 00:34:24,206
So I can make it,
"Her parents want."


691
00:34:24,815 --> 00:34:28,416
If I add the word "see",
for example, I can say,


692
00:34:28,416 --> 00:34:30,866
"Her parents want to see."


693
00:34:30,866 --> 00:34:33,516
And I can drag the word
"you" and I can make it,


694
00:34:33,516 --> 00:34:35,216
"Her parents want to see you."


695
00:34:36,096 --> 00:34:38,005
In fact, I can do even more
complicated things here.


696
00:34:38,146 --> 00:34:41,226
I can say that all of
this happened in the past.


697
00:34:41,485 --> 00:34:43,806
And I don't have to use the
rules of grammar to do this.


698
00:34:43,866 --> 00:34:45,416
All I can do is I
can tap the button


699
00:34:45,416 --> 00:34:46,356
at the bottom that says Past.


700
00:34:46,356 --> 00:34:50,636
It will say, "Her parents
wanted to see you."


701
00:34:51,045 --> 00:34:52,016
And I can negate that.


702
00:34:52,016 --> 00:34:54,576
So if I press the Not button
at the bottom, it will say,


703
00:34:54,576 --> 00:34:57,166
"Her parents didn't
want to see you."


704
00:34:57,816 --> 00:34:59,176
I can make a question out of it.


705
00:34:59,176 --> 00:35:01,276
>> Didn't her parents
didn't want to see you.


706
00:35:01,276 --> 00:35:03,956
>> Or I can make even more
complicated questions.


707
00:35:04,516 --> 00:35:06,586
[ Applause ]


708
00:35:07,086 --> 00:35:08,976
>> Why didn't her
parents want to see you.


709
00:35:09,516 --> 00:35:11,546
[ Applause ]


710
00:35:12,046 --> 00:35:12,346
Thank you.


711
00:35:13,616 --> 00:35:13,986
Thank you.


712
00:35:14,366 --> 00:35:15,616
So that's how FreeSpeech works.


713
00:35:15,616 --> 00:35:17,216
And FreeSpeech is pretty amazing


714
00:35:17,826 --> 00:35:20,056
because I think it's
the very first time


715
00:35:20,056 --> 00:35:23,056
that someone has actually come
up with a grammar predictor.


716
00:35:23,956 --> 00:35:25,176
That's what the app
is doing, right?


717
00:35:25,176 --> 00:35:26,866
I mean, you have all of
these different pictures


718
00:35:26,866 --> 00:35:29,246
and the app is putting
grammar around it.


719
00:35:29,976 --> 00:35:32,026
Now why is that important
for kids with autism?


720
00:35:32,426 --> 00:35:35,506
The best way to kind of explain
that is to draw an analogy


721
00:35:35,506 --> 00:35:36,656
to a different disability.


722
00:35:36,786 --> 00:35:39,126
I'm sure many of you here
have heard of dyslexia.


723
00:35:39,506 --> 00:35:40,666
Some of you may have
even struggled


724
00:35:40,666 --> 00:35:41,506
with it when you were kids.


725
00:35:42,086 --> 00:35:44,546
Kids with dyslexia have a lot
of difficulty with spelling.


726
00:35:44,976 --> 00:35:46,556
You know, English
spelling is horrible.


727
00:35:46,616 --> 00:35:48,376
I have difficulty
with English spelling.


728
00:35:49,116 --> 00:35:51,996
But if you give a kid
with dyslexia an iPad


729
00:35:51,996 --> 00:35:54,086
and you ask them to type,


730
00:35:55,206 --> 00:35:57,336
magically their disability
goes away.


