00:47:53,546 --> 00:47:58,936
Of all people, it was
published by the NSA.


982
00:47:58,936 --> 00:48:03,246
So there was this spy
master probably in the NSA


983
00:48:03,246 --> 00:48:04,486
who did this very
interesting study.


984
00:48:04,486 --> 00:48:07,696
He took a bunch of the
world's languages and he tried


985
00:48:07,696 --> 00:48:11,116
to sort them, he tried to
order them in the order


986
00:48:11,116 --> 00:48:13,156
of which language is
the most difficult


987
00:48:13,756 --> 00:48:15,296
for an English-speaker to speak.


988
00:48:15,296 --> 00:48:18,356
Which one do you
think came out on top?


989
00:48:19,516 --> 00:48:25,626
[ Laughter ]


990
00:48:26,126 --> 00:48:27,426
Well, number 3 was Arabic.


991
00:48:28,656 --> 00:48:29,506
Any Arabic speakers?


992
00:48:31,296 --> 00:48:32,686
Number 2 was Korean.


993
00:48:33,766 --> 00:48:36,686
And number 1 was Japanese.


994
00:48:38,526 --> 00:48:39,776
Any Japanese speakers here?


995
00:48:40,896 --> 00:48:41,926
OK, wow. All right.


996
00:48:42,526 --> 00:48:45,976
So, the native Japanese
speakers here, congratulations.


997
00:48:46,196 --> 00:48:48,506
The NSA thinks yours is the most
difficult language to learn.


998
00:48:48,506 --> 00:48:49,986
And by the time you
were three years old,


999
00:48:50,346 --> 00:48:51,896
you were speaking
Japanese fluently.


1000
00:48:52,286 --> 00:48:58,016
You know, why do kids
learn language so easily?


1001
00:48:58,016 --> 00:48:59,956
It always frustrates me.


1002
00:48:59,956 --> 00:49:01,356
It always makes me very jealous.


1003
00:49:01,356 --> 00:49:02,316
You know, I have a little son.


1004
00:49:02,316 --> 00:49:03,326
He's one and a half years old.


1005
00:49:03,756 --> 00:49:07,556
And I know that in another
one and a half years,


1006
00:49:07,886 --> 00:49:11,106
he'll be speaking
completely fluently.


1007
00:49:11,106 --> 00:49:14,106
And it's always been
a source of puzzlement


1008
00:49:14,106 --> 00:49:15,426
to me in why they do that.


1009
00:49:15,966 --> 00:49:18,586
What the theory says
-- what the theory


1010
00:49:18,586 --> 00:49:19,766
of language acquisition says --


1011
00:49:19,766 --> 00:49:22,886
is that kids learn a
language much faster


1012
00:49:22,886 --> 00:49:25,336
and much more effectively
than adults


1013
00:49:25,336 --> 00:49:26,696
because they're immersed in it.


1014
00:49:27,196 --> 00:49:30,696
You know, they hear it,
they try to speak it,


1015
00:49:31,106 --> 00:49:33,386
and they know what the meaning
is of what's being said to them


1016
00:49:33,386 --> 00:49:35,046
because they understand
the context


1017
00:49:35,046 --> 00:49:35,876
in which it's being said.


1018
00:49:37,206 --> 00:49:39,566
What if we could
simulate emotion


1019
00:49:39,566 --> 00:49:43,836
and provide the same capability
to adults and older children?


1020
00:49:44,996 --> 00:49:47,966
That's why I'm excited about
the prospect of FreeSpeech.


1021
00:49:47,966 --> 00:49:49,986
Because with FreeSpeech,
you're making these sentences,


1022
00:49:50,266 --> 00:49:51,516
and you know what the meaning is


1023
00:49:51,516 --> 00:49:53,116
because you're using
pictures as a bridge.


1024
00:49:53,866 --> 00:49:56,296
And every time you make
sentences in FreeSpeech,


1025
00:49:56,806 --> 00:49:59,126
the app is telling you
what the sentence means


1026
00:49:59,476 --> 00:50:00,946
in the language you're
trying to learn.


1027
00:50:00,946 --> 00:50:03,856
That's the interesting thing,


1028
00:50:03,856 --> 00:50:05,656
and that's what we're
working on.


1029
00:50:07,076 --> 00:50:10,396
You know, language is something


1030
00:50:10,396 --> 00:50:13,566
which is really interesting
for multiple reasons.


1031
00:50:14,126 --> 00:50:19,476
In this connected world
where anyone anywhere


1032
00:50:19,476 --> 00:50:23,546
in the world is two clicks away
on Facebook or on WhatsApp,


1033
00:50:24,506 --> 00:50:26,386
language is really
the last barrier


1034
00:50:26,386 --> 00:50:27,556
that we have as a species.


1035
00:50:28,356 --> 00:50:29,586
I mean, think about it.


1036
00:50:29,586 --> 00:50:32,096
Right? How many of
you have a friend


1037
00:50:32,726 --> 00:50:34,736
with whom you don't
share any language?


1038
00:50:36,956 --> 00:50:40,636
You know, communication
is the fundamental barrier


1039
00:50:40,636 --> 00:50:42,656
that children with
disabilities are born with.


1040
00:50:42,656 --> 00:50:46,446
But it's also the last barrier
that we have to cross as people.


1041
00:50:46,446 --> 00:50:48,786
And that's why the
work that I do is


1042
00:50:48,786 --> 00:50:50,716
so satisfying and
exciting to me.


1043
00:50:51,546 --> 00:50:55,436
You know, I build apps that
help kids with disabilities,


1044
00:50:55,746 --> 00:51:00,206
kids with disadvantaged
education backgrounds, refugees.


1045
00:51:00,206 --> 00:51:04,306
You know, I build apps
that use Apple's devices


1046
00:51:04,306 --> 00:51:05,816
to make the lives of
these people better.


1047
00:51:06,616 --> 00:51:08,026
But I'm hopeful that
some of the work


1048
00:51:08,026 --> 00:51:12,186
that I'm doing could
also help all of us look


1049
00:51:12,186 --> 00:51:14,556
with a different light and
with a different appreciation


1050
00:51:15,016 --> 00:51:18,366
at the most beautiful,
most expressive


1051
00:51:18,806 --> 00:51:21,016
of human inventions -- language.


1052
00:51:22,056 --> 00:51:22,396
Thank you.


1053
00:51:23,516 --> 00:51:29,500
